hands_on_practices.solution:
1.  The poles are at $z=\pm a$. The residue formula for a simple pole $z_0$ is:
   $$\mathrm{Res}_{z=z_0}\frac{H_0^{(1)}(z)}{z^2-a^2}
     =\lim_{z\to z_0}(z-z_0)\frac{H_0^{(1)}(z)}{(z-a)(z+a)}.$$
2.  At $z=a$:
   $$\mathrm{Res}_{z=a} = \frac{H_0^{(1)}(a)}{2a}.$$
3.  At $z=-a$:
   $$\mathrm{Res}_{z=-a} 
     = \lim_{z\to -a} \frac{(z+a)H_0^{(1)}(z)}{(z-a)(z+a)}
     = \frac{H_0^{(1)}(-a)}{-2a}.$$
4.  Using the analytic continuation formula for order zero:
   $$H_0^{(1)}(-a)=H_0^{(1)}(a e^{i\pi})
     = -H_0^{(2)}(a).$$
   So, the residue at $z=-a$ is $\frac{-H_0^{(2)}(a)}{-2a} = \frac{H_0^{(2)}(a)}{2a}$.
5.  Sum of residues:
   $$\mathrm{Res}_{z=a}+\mathrm{Res}_{z=-a}
   =\frac{H_0^{(1)}(a)}{2a} + \frac{H_0^{(2)}(a)}{2a}
   =\frac{H_0^{(1)}(a)+H_0^{(2)}(a)}{2a}
   =\frac{2J_0(a)}{2a}=\frac{J_0(a)}{a}.$$
6.  By the residue theorem (the large-R circle avoids the branch cut), the integral is $2\pi i$ times the sum of the residues inside the contour:
   $$I=2\pi i\sum_{\text{poles inside}} \mathrm{Res}
     =2\pi i\frac{J_0(a)}{a}.$$
